      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Note From the Dead</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Vald Svekis letter responds to Oct 27 front-page article on note found on body of Lt Capt Dimitri Kolesnikov, recovered from sunken Russian submarine Kursk; marvels at courage of Russian government in releasing note; suggests US would have classified such a note and buried it in National Archives (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The note found on the body of Lt. Capt. Dimitri Kolesnikov attests to the hopelessness aboard the sunken Russian submarine ('' 'None of Us Can Get Out,' Kursk Sailor Wrote,'' front page, Oct. 27). Now the sailors have a human face, not just an anonymous end at the bottom of the sea.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The note found on the body of Lt. Capt. Dimitri Kolesnikov attests to the hopelessness aboard the sunken Russian submarine ('' 'None of Us Can Get Out,' Kursk Sailor Wrote,'' front page, Oct. 27). Now the sailors have a human face, not just an anonymous end at the bottom of the sea.</p>
        <p>But most astounding is that the contents of the note were released at all. The resulting recriminations to the highest levels of the Russian government had to be evident, yet the note was released.</p>
        <p>What if the tragedy had been ours? There is little doubt that the note would have been instantly classified and deep-sixed in the Pentagon. At best it would have been marooned in the National Archives with a 50-year time lock.</p>
        <p>The Russians will learn.</p>
        <p>VALD SVEKIS  Sarasota, Fla., Oct. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
